  <section class="faq-section"><div class="container">
    <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">FAQs</span><h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2><p>Common questions about secured credit cards and building credit</p></div>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">What happens to my FD when I get a secured credit card?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Your fixed deposit remains in your bank account and continues to earn interest at the applicable FD rate (currently 6-7% p.a. for most banks). However, the FD is placed under a lien, meaning you cannot withdraw or break it while the credit card is active. If you close the credit card and clear all dues, the lien is removed and you regain full access to your FD. If you default on credit card payments, the bank can break the FD to recover the outstanding amount — which is why secured cards have nearly zero risk for banks.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Can a secured card really improve my CIBIL score?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Absolutely. Secured credit cards are reported to all major credit bureaus (CIBIL, Experian, Equifax) just like regular cards. Every on-time payment, your credit utilisation ratio, and account age all contribute to your credit score. Most people see a 50-100 point improvement in their CIBIL score within 6-12 months of responsible secured card usage. The key is to keep utilisation below 30%, always pay the full amount before due date, and use the card regularly. After building a score of 700+, you can apply for regular unsecured credit cards.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">How much credit limit will I get on a secured card?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Most banks offer a credit limit equal to 80-90% of your FD value. For example, if you place an FD of ₹50,000, your credit limit will be ₹40,000-₹45,000. Some banks like ICICI offer up to 90% while others like SBI offer 80%. To get a higher credit limit, simply place a larger FD. The maximum FD accepted for secured cards is typically ₹5,00,000, giving you a potential credit limit of ₹4,00,000-₹4,50,000 — which is comparable to many regular mid-tier cards.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">When can I upgrade from a secured to an unsecured card?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Most banks review your account after 12-18 months of responsible usage. If you've maintained a clean payment record with no defaults, kept utilisation reasonable, and your CIBIL score has improved to 700+, the bank may offer to upgrade you to a regular unsecured credit card. Upon upgrade, your FD lien is removed and you get full access to your deposit. Some banks like ICICI and Kotak offer automatic upgrade evaluations, while others require you to contact customer service and request the upgrade.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Is a secured card the same as a prepaid card?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">No, they are fundamentally different. A prepaid card requires you to load money before spending — it's like a gift card and does NOT build credit history since it's not reported to credit bureaus. A secured credit card is a real credit card with a billing cycle, interest rates, and credit reporting — the FD is just collateral, not a spending balance. You still get a monthly bill, a grace period, and the option to pay minimum due or full amount. Only secured credit cards help build your CIBIL score; prepaid cards have zero impact on your credit profile.</div></div></div>
    </div>
